DataElement.preferredDefinition: The type of tumor submitted/identified upon slide review.

DataElementConcept.preferredDefinition: information relating to the histologic primary classification of ovarian carcinoma._

ObjectClass.preferredDefinition: A malignant neoplasm originating from the surface ovarian epithelium.  It accounts for the greatest number of deaths from malignancies of the female genital tract and is the fifth leading cause of cancer fatalities in women.  It is predominantly a disease of older white women of northern European extraction, but it is seen in all ages and ethnic groups.  Adenocarcinomas constitute the vast majority of ovarian carcinomas.  The pattern of metastatic spread in ovarian carcinoma is similar regardless of the microscopic type.  The most common sites of involvement are the contralateral ovary, peritoneal cavity, para-aortic and pelvic lymph nodes, and liver.  Lung and pleura are the most common sites of extra-abdominal spread.  The primary form of therapy is surgical.  The overall prognosis of ovarian carcinoma remains poor, a direct result of its rapid growth rate and the lack of early symptoms. --2002

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A benign or malignant neoplasm that arises from the ovary and is composed of granulosa cells, Sertoli cells, Leydig cells, theca cells, and fibroblasts.  Representative examples include thecoma, fibroma, Sertoli cell tumor, and granulosa cell tumor.

Concepts.definition: A benign or malignant neoplasm that arises from the ovary and is composed of granulosa cells, Sertoli cells, Leydig cells, theca cells, and fibroblasts.  Representative examples include thecoma, fibroma, Sertoli cell tumor, and granulosa cell tumor.

ValueMeaning.changeDescription: Concept annotation added for UPitt/TCGA.  Ylu, 02/24/2015.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An aggressive carcinoma arising from the ovary.  Most patients present with advanced disease.  Microscopically, it is characterized by significant cytologic atypia, increased mitotic activity, and necrosis.  The prognosis is usually poor.

Concepts.definition: An aggressive carcinoma arising from the ovary.  Most patients present with advanced disease.  Microscopically, it is characterized by significant cytologic atypia, increased mitotic activity, and necrosis.  The prognosis is usually poor.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A carcinoma that arises from the ovary and is characterized by the presence of malignant epithelial cells that resemble malignant urothelial cells.  There is no morphologic evidence of a benign or borderline Brenner tumor component present.

Concepts.definition: A carcinoma that arises from the ovary and is characterized by the presence of malignant epithelial cells that resemble malignant urothelial cells.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An ovarian epithelial neoplasm that resembles the transitional cell neoplasms found in the urinary tract. It is characterized by the presence of atypia and absence of stromal invasion.

Concepts.definition: An ovarian epithelial neoplasm that resembles the transitional cell neoplasms found in the urinary tract. It is characterized by the presence of atypia and absence of stromal invasion.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A usually high grade squamous cell carcinoma that arises from the ovary and is not associated with a germ cell tumor.  The prognosis is poor.

Concepts.definition: A usually high grade squamous cell carcinoma that arises from the ovary and is not associated with a germ cell tumor.  The prognosis is poor.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A malignant serous cystic epithelial neoplasm arising from the ovary.  It is characterized by the presence of glandular, papillary, or solid structures.  Psammoma bodies may be present.  In well differentiated cases the malignant epithelial cells resemble the cells of fallopian tube epithelium.  In poorly differentiated cases the malignant epithelial cells show anaplastic features.

Concepts.definition: A malignant serous cystic epithelial neoplasm arising from the ovary.  It is characterized by the presence of glandular, papillary, or solid structures.  Psammoma bodies may be present.  In well differentiated cases the malignant epithelial cells resemble the cells of fallopian tube epithelium.  In poorly differentiated cases the malignant epithelial cells show anaplastic features.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Ovarian serous adenocarcinoma is a serous neoplasm characterized by nuclear atypia, high mitotic activity, stratification, glandular complexity, branching papillary fronds and stromal invasion. --2002

Concepts.definition: An adenocarcinoma that arises from the ovary and is characterized by the presence of malignant epithelial cells that, in well differentiated tumors, resemble the epithelium of the fallopian tube or, in poorly differentiated tumors, show anaplastic features and marked nuclear atypia.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A low grade serous epithelial neoplasm arising from the ovary.  It is characterized by an atypical proliferation of serous-type epithelial cells without evidence of stromal invasion.  It is often asymptomatic but rarely it may present with abdominal pain or abdominal enlargement due to rupture or torsion.

Concepts.definition: A low grade serous epithelial neoplasm arising from the ovary.  It is characterized by an atypical proliferation of serous-type epithelial cells without evidence of stromal invasion.  It is often asymptomatic but rarely it may present with abdominal pain or abdominal enlargement due to rupture or torsion.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An invasive cystic adenocarcinoma arising from the ovary.  It is characterized by the presence of malignant glandular epithelial cells which contain intracytoplasmic mucin.  The malignant cells invade the ovarian stroma and the cystic spaces contain mucoid material.  In a minority of cases both ovaries are involved by the tumor.  The prognosis for stage I tumors is excellent.  Patients with metastases usually have a poor prognosis.

Concepts.definition: An invasive cystic adenocarcinoma arising from the ovary.  It is characterized by the presence of malignant glandular epithelial cells which contain intracytoplasmic mucin.  The malignant cells invade the ovarian stroma and the cystic spaces contain mucoid material.  In a minority of cases both ovaries are involved by the tumor.  The prognosis for stage I tumors is excellent.  Patients with metastases usually have a poor prognosis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An invasive adenocarcinoma that arises from the ovary and is characterized by the presence of malignant epithelial cells that contain intracytoplasmic mucin.  There is cellular atypia, increased layering of cells, complexity of glands, and papillary formations.

Concepts.definition: An invasive adenocarcinoma that arises from the ovary and is characterized by the presence of malignant epithelial cells that contain intracytoplasmic mucin.  There is cellular atypia, increased layering of cells, complexity of glands, and papillary formations.

PermissibleValues.value: Mucinous borderline tumor, intestinal type (WHO code: 3472/1)
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Borderline Ovarian Mucinous Tumor, Intestinal Type

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Borderline Ovarian Mucinous Tumor, Intestinal Type
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A neoplasm of low malignant potential arising from the ovary.  It is characterized by the proliferation of neoplastic mucinous epithelial cells that resemble intestinal epithelial cells.  There is no evidence of stromal invasion.

Concepts.longName: Borderline Ovarian Mucinous Tumor, Intestinal Type
Concepts.definition: A neoplasm of low malignant potential arising from the ovary.  It is characterized by the proliferation of neoplastic mucinous epithelial cells that resemble intestinal epithelial cells.  There is no evidence of stromal invasion.

PermissibleValues.value: Mucinous borderline tumor, endocervical (seromuninous) type (WHO code: 8472/1)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A neoplasm of low malignant potential arising from the ovary.  It is characterized by the proliferation of neoplastic epithelial cells that resemble endocervical epithelial cells.  There is no evidence of stromal invasion.

Concepts.definition: A neoplasm of low malignant potential arising from the ovary.  It is characterized by the proliferation of neoplastic epithelial cells that resemble endocervical epithelial cells.  There is no evidence of stromal invasion.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A malignant mixed epithelial neoplasm that arises from the ovary and is composed predominantly of serous and endocervical-type mucinous epithelium.

Concepts.definition: A malignant mixed epithelial neoplasm that arises from the ovary and is composed predominantly of serous and endocervical-type mucinous cells.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A low grade ovarian epithelial tumor composed of an admixture of two or more of the five major cell types: serous, mucinous, endometrioid, clear cell, and Brenner/transitional.  The second or second and third cell types must comprise alone or together at least 10% of the tumor epithelium. The majority of patients present with stage I tumor and a minority present with bilateral disease. Morphologically, it shows papillae with detached cell clusters.  Microinvasion may be seen rarely. (WHO 2003)

Concepts.longName: Borderline Ovarian Seromucinous Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Seromucinous Tumor
Concepts.definition: A low grade, non-invasive ovarian epithelial neoplasm characterized by the presence of atypical neoplastic serous and mucinous cells.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An invasive malignant neoplasm that arises from the ovary and originates from primordial germ cells.  Representative examples include embryonal carcinoma, yolk sac tumor, dysgerminoma, and non-gestational choriocarcinoma.

Concepts.definition: An invasive malignant neoplasm that arises from the ovary and originates from primordial germ cells.  Representative examples include embryonal carcinoma, yolk sac tumor, dysgerminoma, and non-gestational choriocarcinoma.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A granulosa-stromal cell tumor that arises from the ovary.  It is characterized by the presence of granulosa cells that comprise at least ten percent of the cellular population.  The granulosa cells are often found in a background that contains theca and fibrous cells.  There are two major subtypes recognized, adult and juvenile granulosa cell tumor.  Clinically, patients may present with an abdominal mass.  Symptoms depend on the patient's age.  The most important indicator of prognosis is tumor stage.  Age over forty years at the time of the initial diagnosis, large tumor size, bilaterality, cellular atypia, and increased mitotic activity are factors indicating a potentially aggressive clinical course and relative poor prognosis.

Concepts.definition: A granulosa-stromal cell tumor that arises from the ovary.  It is characterized by the presence of granulosa cells that comprise at least ten percent of the cellular population.  The granulosa cells are often found in a background that contains theca and fibrous cells.  There are two major subtypes recognized, adult and juvenile granulosa cell tumor.  Clinically, patients may present with an abdominal mass.  Symptoms depend on the patient's age.  The most important indicator of prognosis is tumor stage.  Age over forty years at the time of the initial diagnosis, large tumor size, bilaterality, cellular atypia, and increased mitotic activity are factors indicating a potentially aggressive clinical course and relative poor prognosis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An endometrioid adenocarcinoma arising from the ovary.  It comprises 10% to 25% of all primary ovarian carcinomas.  Grossly, endometrioid carcinoma may present as a cystic or solid mass.  Microscopically, the tumor greatly resembles the appearance of the ordinary type of endometrial adenocarcinoma.  As a group, endometrioid carcinoma has a prognosis twice as good as that of serous or mucinous carcinoma.

Concepts.definition: An endometrioid adenocarcinoma arising from the ovary.  It comprises 10% to 25% of all primary ovarian carcinomas.  Grossly, endometrioid carcinoma may present as a cystic or solid mass.  Microscopically, the tumor greatly resembles the appearance of the ordinary type of endometrial adenocarcinoma.  As a group, endometrioid carcinoma has a prognosis twice as good as that of serous or mucinous carcinoma.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A neoplasm of low malignant potential arising from the ovary. It is characterized by the presence of glandular or cystic spaces which contain atypical glandular epithelial cells resembling endometrial cells. The surrounding ovarian stroma is often fibrotic. There is no evidence of stromal invasion.

Concepts.longName: Borderline Ovarian Endometrioid Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Endometrioid Tumor
Concepts.definition: An epithelial neoplasm that arises from the ovary characterized by the presence of glandular or cystic spaces which contain atypical glandular epithelial cells resembling endometrial cells. The surrounding ovarian stroma is often fibrotic. There is no evidence of stromal invasion.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A malignant neoplasm composed of glandular epithelial clear cells.  Various architectural patterns may be seen, including papillary, tubulocystic, and solid.

Concepts.definition: A malignant neoplasm composed of glandular epithelial clear cells.  Various architectural patterns may be seen, including papillary, tubulocystic, and solid.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An epithelial neoplasm with low malignant potential affecting the ovary.  It is characterized by the presence of clear or hobnail cells.  In some cases, the cells may display nuclear atypia and prominent nucleoli.  When such cells are present, they remain confined to the glands.  There is no evidence of stromal invasion.

Concepts.definition: An epithelial neoplasm with low malignant potential affecting the ovary.  It is characterized by the presence of clear or hobnail cells.  In some cases, the cells may display nuclear atypia and prominent nucleoli.  When such cells are present, they remain confined to the glands.  There is no evidence of stromal invasion.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A malignant tumor composed of a mixture of carcinomatous and sarcomatous elements.

Concepts.definition: A malignant tumor composed of a mixture of carcinomatous and sarcomatous elements.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A Brenner tumor of the ovary characterized by a cytologically malignant cell population and stromal invasion.

Concepts.definition: A malignant neoplasm that arises from the ovary. It is characterized by the presence of an invasive malignant urothelial-type cellular component and nests of benign urothelial-type cells in a fibrotic stroma. When the neoplasm is confined to the ovary, the prognosis is good.
